solution.text:
Maximum possible magnetic field is at the surface
$\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{B}_{\max }=\frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{I}}{2 \pi \mathrm{a}} \\
& \frac{\mathrm{~B}_{\max }}{2}=\frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{I}}{4 \pi \mathrm{a}}
\end{aligned}$

It can be obtained inside as well as outside the wire For inside,
$\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{I}}{4 \pi \mathrm{a}}=\frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{Ir}}{2 \pi \mathrm{a}^2} \\
& \Rightarrow \mathrm{r}=\frac{\mathrm{a}}{2}
\end{aligned}$

For outside
$\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{I}}{4 \pi \mathrm{a}}=\frac{\mu_0 \mathrm{I}}{2 \pi \mathrm{r}} \\
& \Rightarrow \mathrm{r}=2 \mathrm{a}
\end{aligned}$

Correct answer $\left[\frac{\mathrm{a}}{2}, 2 \mathrm{a}\right]$
